3. Exploratory findings

A. Annual juvenile hare trap counts

Figure 1. Total number of juvenile snowshoe hare trappings by year (1999 to 2012) across all grid sites in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest, Alaska. Data: Kielland et al. (2017).

Over the course of the study, the minimum count of juvenile hare trappings that occurred in a single year was 2 hares (2010). The maximum count of juvenile trappings that occurred in a single year was 126 hares (1999). The annual mean and median counts of juvenile hares were 31 and 18, respectively. Overall, the number of juvenile trappings tended to decrease over time, aside from two substantial increases relative to previous years, which occurred in 2005 and 2008. In future analyses, the juvenile hare population data could be standardized by converting observations to z-scores. This would allow annual juvenile trappings to be compared based on the number of standard deviations they are from the mean value.

B. Visualization of juvenile hare weights

Figure 2. Weight observations (g) of juvenile male and female snowshoe hares for each trapping grid site (Bonanza Mature forest, Bonanza Riparian forest, and Bonanza Black Spruce forest). Pink (female) and teal (male) points indicate individual observations for weight (grams) of juvenile snowshoe hares. Box endpoints indicate the 25th and 75th percentile values; the black line indicates the median for each sex at the different grid sites. Outliers are indicated by black points. Data: Kielland et al. (2017).

Juvenile snowshoe hare weights were compared by sex and grid site. There were notable outliers in the female sample from the Bonanza Riparian site and in the male sample from the Bonanza Black Spruce site. Median values were similar across the different grids for both male and female groups. Each group had a relatively large spread, with many overlapping points between groups of both males and females and across grid sites. Some of the juvenile groups, including Bonanza Riparian females and Bonanza Mature males, appeared to have a bimodal distribution rather than relative distributions.

C. Juvenile weight comparison (male and female snowshoe hares)

Table 1. Descriptive statistics (mean, standard deviation, and sample size) for weight of female and male juvenile snowshoe hares.

Sex Mean weight (g) Standard deviation Sample size
Female 855.3909 292.2526 197
Male 945.8589 333.2151 163

Distributions of weights for male and female juvenile snowshoe hares were relatively normal and symmetric. On average, male juvenile snowshoe hares weighed more than juvenile females (945.86 \(\pm\) 333.22 and 855.39 \(\pm\) 292.25 g, respectively; mean \(\pm\) 1 standard deviation). The absolute difference in means is 90.47 g (a 10.05% difference), and is significant (Welch’s two-sample t-test: t(325.02) = 2.71, p = 0.01. While the difference in means is significant, the effect size is small (Cohen’s d = (0.29).

D. Relationship between juvenile hare weight and hind foot length

Figure 3. Relationship between hind foot length (mm) and weight (g) for all juvenile snowshoe hares. Points indicate individual juvenile hare measurements. Kielland et al. (2017).

C. Linear regression analysis

Simple linear regression was used to explore the relationship between juvenile snowshoe hare hind foot length (mm) and weight (g) across all grid sites, including both male and female juveniles. A significant regression model was found (p <0.001, R2 = 0.3), with an average slope of \(\beta\) = 9.52 g/mm-1 (i.e., 29.9% of variance in juvenile snowshoe weight is explained by hind foot length, and for each one mm increase in hind foot length we expect an average increase in weight of 9.52 g). Pearson’s r is equal to 0.55, indicating a moderate association between hind foot length and weight. However, diagnostic plots (not included) show a trend in variance, violating the assumption of homoscedasticity. Diagnostic plots also show that residuals are not normally distributed about the model and that there are outliers that may have too much leverage on the model. Due to these violations of assumptions, linear regression may not describe the model well.
